  "why": "The paper mutates image inputs in in-memory/continuous representations (including pixel-level float perturbations and normalized inputs used for GAN training) and does not describe enforcing serialization-level constraints (e.g., clipping/rounding to 0–255 integer pixel values) nor generating inputs directly in serialized formats (PNG/JPEG). DRFuzz normalizes pixels to [0,1] for GAN training and applies pixel-level Gaussian/noise and image-level transforms in-memory (0.5% pixel mutations, patch operations, scaling/rotation, etc.), but there is no mention of converting or constraining mutated values to the discrete/serialized image format or of verifying that mutations survive saving to disk. Therefore the method fits the metric definition for Low: mutating in continuous/normalized representations without enforcing format constraints.",
